entry.title: Add feature top level type to mojo
entry.content:
Adds a top level `feature` pseudo-type to the mojo language[0].



Mojo files can now contain a `feature` top level item. The

keyword is not reserved in other places in mojo files, so

e.g. a method can continue to have a parameter named

`feature`.



```

module foo;



[Attribute=Value]

feature {

const string field = "value";

// ...

};

```



At the mojo language level `feature` will be used as

an attribute on interfaces and methods to allow runtime

control of interface binding and method availability. Specific

bindings will determine what `feature` means in their context

and which fields `feature` supports or requires.



features may appear as attribute values - attribute value lookup

is improved to allow this to return the underlying type inside

the parser.



[0] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1kKFHu73SNwpBfPJzrVH2vLbpu9_1WuZhngFBqtJhwqw/edit?pli=1



Tests: .\mojo\public\tools\run_all_python_unittests.py

entry.title: Don't deregister side panel entry from NTP destructor if still needed
entry.content:
With RenderDocument, cross-document navigations will use new

RenderFrameHosts, which also causes new WebUI objects (e.g. for NTP)

to be created on document reloads. This caused a bug with side

panel entries that are registered/deregistered from NTP constructor

and destructor: when the new NTP object is created it didn't create

a new side panel entry as the previous NTP object hasn't been

destructed yet, but when the previous NTP object is finally

destructed, the side panel entry that is still used by the new NTP

object will accidentally get deleted (see linked bug).



This CL fixes the bug by not deleting the side panel entry if it's

still being used (i.e. when the WebContents is still using the NTP).

entry.title: Set macOS printer for OOP system print
entry.content:
The macOS platform requires that the system print dialog be displayed

from the browser process. For out-of-process printing, the dialog data

is transferred to the Print Backend service and the platform print

settings are reconstituted.



Establishing the destination parameters was missing a call to set the

destination printer. This could silently succeed if the user has only

one printer installed, or if all installed printers are just driver

varitations to the same real device. A computer with drivers for

multiple different printers installed could fail to select the intended

device that was selected in the system print dialog. Additionally,

since the devices could be completely different, then specifying the

print settings could fail with invalid parameters.



Correct this by applying the destination settings before other print

settings and the page format. Specify the selected target printer as

part of applying the destination settings.



Along the way also update error reporting to use the Apple-specific

logging calls to display helpful strings for OSStatus errors.



Low-Coverage-Reason: HARD_TO_TEST, system dialog interaction

RGBA-but-really-BGRA behavior when using Ganesh/GL.

entry.title: Add weak feature keyword to mojo
entry.content:
This CL adds a top-level keyword `feature` to mojo[0]. Unlike existing

keywords this token is used widely in existing mojo definitions

so it is not sensible to reserve this keyword - instead it is introduced

as a weak keyword - where it will be parsed as a feature token if

used as a top-level token (e.g. where mojo would expect to see

'interface', 'struct' etc.) but as a normal token in other places.



When used at the top level `feature` throws a parse error. Following

CLs will implement the use of the keyword to allow mojo to be

aware of runtime features. This CL mainly serves to add the

`name_wrapped` helper to the mojo parser, and isolates formatting

changes that result. Presubmit line length checks on parser.py

have been removed - python's lex/yacc modules use function level

comments when defining their grammar and wrapping these is awkward.



[0] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1kKFHu73SNwpBfPJzrVH2vLbpu9_1WuZhngFBqtJhwqw/edit?pli=1

entry.title: [Select to Speak] Inject clipboard copy in Lacros gdocs tabs
entry.content:
Select to speak tries to speak selected text with search+s,

and uses the a11y tree to determine the selection region. Google

docs does not populate selection on the underlying contenteditable

even when the canvas appears visually selected. As a work-around,

we fire a clipboard copy event from Select to Speak upon search+s

in gdocs and then paste the text within Select to Speak and

read the plain text. For more, see go/sts-selection-in-drive.



This change adds the workaround to Google docs in Lacros tabs,

where chrome.tabs in Ash wasn't able to find the tab or execute

the script. Now STS in Ash requests EmbeddedA11yHelper in Lacros

injects the content script via private extension APIs and

crosapi.



This does not have automated tests because it must be run on

live gdocs pages, and tests on CQ cannot have external

dependencies on gdocs. The original feature in Ash also lacks

automated tests. As a follow-up I will try to add tast tests

for Ash and Lacros.



in Google Docs

entry.title: [APS] Create and show tab cards on hover
entry.content:
This CL adds strip tab text hover card support, with the card containing

tab title and URL information. The CL broadly includes the following

updates:



- Create a new LinearLayout for the tab hover card.

- Determine the width of the hover card, that is subject to change based

on the window width. The hover card should not exceed 90% of the window

width and should always maintain an 8dp lateral margin relative to the

enclosing window.

- Determine the horizontal and vertical positions of the hover card with

respect to the hovered tab, while taking the folio/detached/GM2 tab

shapes and RTL layout into account.

- Update the background and text colors of the hover card based on the

theme and incognito mode.

entry.title: Fix several installer API issues
entry.content:
* Handle installer exit codes correctly.

* Handle additional success codes `ERROR_SUCCESS_REBOOT_INITIATED` and

`ERROR_SUCCESS_RESTART_REQUIRED`.

* Remove `MakeInstallerResultAndOriginalError`, not needed anymore

because of the `update_client` changes in r1199685.

* The CrxInstaller uniformly returns `0` for success, and

`kErrorApplicationInstallerFailed` for failure. The original code is

stored within `original_error` to avoid overlaps with update_client

error codes. Also enabled by the `update_client` changes in r1199685.

This reconciles `update_client::InstallError` code overlaps with app

installer exit codes.

* Handle the offline installer cases similar to the online update_client

cases.
